The grasshopper years of Latin America
Bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
This is hardly surprising since the majority of Latin American countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
Capitals have been sold and national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing durable and beneficial has been achieved.
These years were really eaten up by locusts.
Over the past 20 years, the annual growth rate of per capita GNP in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global market except through timid wage increases?
Economic stagnation is the result of bad governance, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa more and more - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have put it on this path.
First, in the rush toward privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been put up for sale.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, the revenues from privatization have produced little in the context of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the sale of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing undertaken by national buyers exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform did not bring prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The inflow of capital generated a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sane politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be in place to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
Governments that operated according to technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being questioned, and a random and even more corrupt effort at redistribution is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more luck; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and her team, who conduct opinion polls during the period preceding Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already started to flee - even though elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this stability may well prove to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the economically financial result, because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the prosperous 1970s of OPEC - years it did not participate in, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
Argentina's wealth is now taking vacations in Miami, perhaps forever.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saving.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40%, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions support the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
Rewards for risk-taking and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GNP is only half of that of Brazil.
But with growth in China's coastal region at about 15% per year, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the huge problems encountered, things continue to go well, first because of the massive flow of foreign direct investment and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to unravel: governments backtrack on reforms and the economy loses ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds flowed in, but these days are largely over.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political conditions in the years ahead.
Populists such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- a former Argentine presidential candidate -- may seem like a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
